Suppose we have a test class with no test methods:
```java
public class MyJUnit4EmptyTest
{
}
```

Let's run this code:
```java
public class App
{
  public static void main(String[] args)
  {
    int testsCount = Request.aClass(MyJUnit4EmptyTest.class).getRunner().testCount();

    if (testsCount != 0)
    {
      System.err.println("Expected 0 tests count, but was " + testsCount);
    }
}
```

Output:
```
Expected 0 tests count, but was 1
```

The class doesn't have any test methods, but JUnit4 claims that it has 1 test!

Digging into the code of AssumptionViolatedException you will find:
```java
public AssumptionViolatedException(Object value, Matcher<?> matcher) {
	super(value instanceof Throwable ? (Throwable) value : null);
	fValue= value;
	fMatcher= matcher;
}
```
According the documentation of "cause" in `java.lang.Throwable` this states that there is no (known) cause for this exception. If instead the cause is not yet initialized the cause should point to `this` - which is the initial value in Throwable.

For the work I am doing I need to specify a message and a cause. Having the current API this is not possible:

* There is no 2-arg constructor with message and cause
* `initCause()` cannot be called because Throwable does not allow to set the cause twice (and it got set to null before)

For me the solution would be sufficient to introduce a constructor `AssumptionViolatedException(message, cause)`. But the real problem (from my point of view) is the erroneous initialization with `null`.

Currently assertThat only reports a description of the matcher and the expected value. This is OK for simple matchers, but might be next to useless for more complicated matchers. Here, only the Matcher.describeMismatch would help. Thus, I propose to include hamcrest's mismatch reason into the AssertionError's message.

Consider for example this:

    Set<Integer> s1 = new TreeSet<Integer>();
    Set<Integer> s2 = new TreeSet<Integer>();
    for (int i = 1; i < 5; ++i) {
      s1.add(i);
      s2.add(i);
    }
    s1.add(0);
    Assert.assertThat(s1, everyItem(isIn(s2)));

As of JUnit 4.10 this fails with the message:

    Expected: every item is one of {<1>, <2>, <3>, <4>}
         got: <[0, 1, 2, 3, 4]>

If you got large collections you will have a hard time to find out which item is the problem. The crucial information is in the mismatch. I suggest the following format:

    Expected: every item is one of {<1>, <2>, <3>, <4>}
         got: <[0, 1, 2, 3, 4]>
         mismatch: an item was <0>

Alternatively, you might use the same formatting as http://code.google.com/p/hamcrest/source/browse/trunk/hamcrest-java/hamcrest-core/src/main/java/org/hamcrest/MatcherAssert.java .

If I have a test class with at least one theory (meaning I have it marked with @RunsWith(Theories.class), then I can't use Assume in any @Test method without it failing.

If a Theory does not run a single time (all values are assumed away), it makes sense to fail.

But it is accidentally also changing the behavior for methods simply marked @Test.  

Example:


import org.junit.Assume;
import org.junit.Ignore;
import org.junit.Test;
import org.junit.experimental.theories.DataPoint;
import org.junit.experimental.theories.Theories;
import org.junit.experimental.theories.Theory;
import org.junit.runner.RunWith;

@RunWith(Theories.class)
public class ExampleTest
{

    @DataPoint
    public final static boolean TRUE = true;

    @DataPoint
    public final static boolean FALSE = false;

    @Theory
    public void testAssume(boolean assume)
    {
        Assume.assumeTrue(assume);
    }

    @Ignore("This test is ignored because it will fail because tests cannot assume when run by the theories runner")
    @Test
    public void testAssumeFalse()
    {
        Assume.assumeTrue(false);
    }

    @Test
    public void testAssumeTrue()
    {
        Assume.assumeTrue(true);
    }

}
